We will often crucially use some well-known studies published in English for double object constructions in head-initial languages other than English: Chung (1976) for Bahasa Indonesian; Kimenyi (1980) for Kinyarwanda (in the Bantu family); Aissen (1983) for Tzotzil (in the Mayan family); Haegeman (1985) for West Flemish; Baker (1988a) for many non-Indo-European languages; Baker (1988b) and Alsina and Mchombo (1990) for Chiche



a (Bantu); Zhang (1990) and Den Dikken (1995c) for Chinese;
2 Den Dikken (1995c) for all the modern Germanic languages; and Holmberg and Platzack (1995) for Scandinavian languages.

p.span:
51 The wide gamut of double complement structures, many already familiar from Chomsky (1965: ch. 2), includes those of promise (Mary to behave yourself), persuade (Bill it's raining), strike (the childreni
 as dangerous to themi
), prevent (the girls from seeing each other), say (to every student that he's brilliant), speak (two languages to everybody), seem (to John {that/like} it is raining), remind (Mary of her duties), rob (John of money), take (3 hours to eat lunch), taste (spoiled to John), etc. In light of the Barss-Lasnik paradigms, the binary branching hypothesis leads to the conclusion that all the preceding parenthesized strings are constituents, presumably small clauses. This conclusion strikes us as a reductio ad absurdum, but seems not to have deterred proponents of binary branching complementation.
